How the Breach Check Works (K-Anonymity)
This project uses a privacy-preserving technique called k-anonymity to check passwords against breach databases without exposing the actual password:

The password is hashed locally using SHA-1
Only the first 5 characters of that hash are sent to the HaveIBeenPwned API
The API returns all hash suffixes that match that prefix (hundreds of results)
The full hash is matched locally — the real password never leaves your machine

This is the same method used by major browsers and password managers like 1Password.

What I Learned

How password entropy works and what makes credentials resistant to brute-force attacks
The k-anonymity privacy model and why it matters in security tooling
How to build and consume RESTful APIs securely in Python
Flask routing, JSON handling, and serving static assets
Why credential stuffing is dangerous and how breach databases help defend against it


